==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Offence
<hw>Of*fence"</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>offensa</ets>. See
<er>Offend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of offending in any
sense; esp., a crime or a sin, an affront or an injury.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who was delivered for our <qex>offenses</qex>, and was raised
again for our justification.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. iv. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have given my opinion against the authority of two great men,
but I hope without <qex>offense</qex> to their memories.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being offended or displeased; anger;
displeasure; <as>as, to cause <ex>offense</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was content to give them just cause of <qex>offense</qex>, when
they had power to make just revenge.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A cause or occasion of stumbling or of sin.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Woe to that man by whom the <qex>offense</qex> cometh!</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xviii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In any contest, the act or process of attacking as
contrasted with the act of defending; the offensive; <as>as, to go on
the <ex>offense</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>The members of a team who have
the primary responsibility to score goals, in contrast to those who have
the responsibility to defend, i.e. to prevent the opposing team from
scoring goal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word, like <xex>expense</xex>, is often spelled
with a <xex>c</xex>. It ought, however, to undergo the same change with
<xex>expense</xex>, the reasons being the same, namely, that
<xex>s</xex> must be used in <xex>offensive</xex> as in
<xex>expensive</xex>, and is found in the Latin <xex>offensio</xex>, and
the French <xex>offense</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To take offense</b></col>, <cd>to feel, or assume to be,
injured or affronted; to become angry or hostile.</cd> --
<col><b>Weapons of offense</b></col>, <cd>those which are used in
attack, in distinction from those of <xex>defense</xex>, which are used
to repel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Displeasure; umbrage; resentment; misdeed;
misdemeanor; trespass; transgression; delinquency; fault; sin; crime;
affront; indignity; outrage; insult.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Offenseful</ent>⟦br⟧
